SIMPLE: fun
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fun
<hw>Fun</hw> <pr>(f⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. of Celtic
origin; cf. Ir. & Gael. <ets>fonn</ets> pleasure.]</ety> <def>Sport;
merriment; frolicsome amusement.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Oddity, frolic, and
<xex>fun</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To make fun of</b></col>, <cd>to hold up to, or turn
into, ridicule.</cd></cs> -- <col><b>in fun</b></col>, <cd>jokingly; not
seriously; for amusement.</cd> -- <col><b>like fun</b></col>,
<cd>definitely not; -- used adverbially, mostly to contradict a prior
assertion; A: ⟦ldquo⟧He says he won't do it again.⟦rdquo⟧ -- B:
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Like fun</xex> he won't.⟦rdquo⟧.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fun</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: fun
<hw>fun</hw> <pr>(f⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>adj.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>funner</adjf>
<pr>(f⟦ucr⟧n"n⟦etil⟧r)</pr> <mark>(colloquial or jocular)</mark>;
<pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>funnest</adjf> <pr>(f⟦ucr⟧n"n⟦ecr⟧st)</pr>
<mark>(colloquial or jocular)</mark>.]</amorph> <def>Of or pertaining to
fun; causing pleasure or amusement; <as>as, a <ex>fun</ex> thing to
do</as>.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Funafuti</ent>⟦br⟧
